HEADWORD: Synanthrose
<hw>Syn*an"throse"</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧n*⟦acr⟧n"thr⟦omac⟧s)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From NL. <ets>Synantherae</ets> the Compositae; Gr.
<grk>sy`n</grk> with + <grk>'anqh`ros</grk> blooming.]</ety>
<fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>A variety of sugar, isomeric with sucrose, found
in the tubers of the Jerusalem artichoke (<spn>Helianthus
tuberosus</spn>), in the dahlia, and other Compositae.</def><-- ?? not
in Merck I. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

